<div class="breadcrumb"><a href="">Home</a> &raquo; <a href="forum">forums</a> &raquo; <a href="forum/1">LtU Forum</a></div><h2>Why Johnny can&#039;t code</h2>
<!-- begin content -->
<div class="node">
 <div class="content">
<p >Not particularly academic so hope this isn't too off-topic, but thought this article in the non-geek media (salon.com) might interest some here:</p>
<p ><a href="http://www.salon.com/tech/feature/2006/09/14/basic/">Why Johnny can't code</a></p>
<p >'BASIC used to be on every computer a child touched -- but today there's no easy way for kids to get hooked on programming.'</p>
<p >I have to say that, much as I love more modern higher-level languages (why else would I be here), BASIC was what I grew up on, and really was ideal for picking up a first understanding of what programming is all about. With its global variables, GOTOs and all. It gets the computer obeying your command and following your logic with the absolute minimum learning curve. You don't have to learn any more abstractions than are absolutely necessary in order to feel that power (wow, it actually does what I tell it to, step by step!) and get yourself hooked. </p> </div>
 <div class="links">By <a href="user/1147" title="View user profile.">citylight</a> at 09/18/2006 - 22:21 | <a href="taxonomy/term/1">LtU Forum</a> | <a href="node/1738" title="SSA + Type Inference = &amp;quot;Compile time&amp;quot; dynamic typing, &amp;quot;runtime&amp;quot; static typing?">previous forum topic</a> | <a href="node/1742" title="What Makes Erlang Processes Tick?">next forum topic</a> | <a href="http://www.technorati.com/search/lambda-the-ultimate.org/node/1733" title="Technorati search of other blogs commenting on this post.">other blogs</a> | 2808 reads</div>
</div>
